content.description: Nice juggy line on the far left side of the cave. Moves up and left on ledges to a crux in the final 10' of climbing.
content.location: far left side of the cave, 1st from the left

content.description: On the right side of the cave near the entrance. Start on two crimpy jugs and head right into hueco jugs. Top out above roof.

Start in chalked up pockets, move right along the overhang to the arete, then up to the ledge with several options for the finish. Variations get harder from left to right. Topout/traverse off to the right or drop down.
content.location: Located in the recess to the right of Thieving's start.

content.description: This route shares the start with Thieving Texas Scum and then traverses to the left after 2 bolts. Continue up and left then follow the intermittent wide crack out the roof.
Starts deep in the cave and climbs up to a few huecos in the roof where you can cop a couple uncomfortable bat hangs which leads you to the crux of the route at the very end.
Good route, starts in the middle of the cave and exits straight out the roof crack in the middle of the roof, has a small roof halfway up
content.location: starts right of Genetic drift and left of Thieving Texas Scum

content.description: Starting in the graffitied hueco in the back left of the of the cave room, (bottom left section of cub cave), pull some hard roof moves until you get to a good rest at the exit of the smaller cave, then fight the pump to the top out of cub cave. About 30 power endurance moves on roof in total, what more can you ask for?
content.location: Furthest left and deepest section of cub cave.

content.description: Jug pulling to a nice little finishing crux pulling the final lip.
content.location: 3rd route from the left, lower from last bolt

content.description: Crimpy start to jugs, then crux boulder problem in the roof. Good moves on solid stone.

Sit start with hands in the horizontal crack. Move up towards the large tufa then make one more reach to a jug to finish the problem. The tufa is usually wet on the bottom, but positive features make the hold usable in damp conditions. Makes for a great full value start to Surfing in San Antonio.  

 I'm assuming this is a first ascent since there was no chalk prior to the tufa, but please let me know if I was incorrect and I'll update the FA info.
content.location: Below/left of Surfing in San Antonio. Start is just to the left of a large broken off block.

content.description:
This is a fantastic climb to the left of White Trash (5.12a). The rocky slope is close enough to pad it out so a rope is not necessary. It is a long climb for a boulder problem and there is one long move that felt in the 5.11+ range.

 Start standing at the opening of a deep cave and climb out on good holds and top out.

 Note: I named it "Bear Bones" because it is better than "unknown" change it if you want. -Ross
Shady, overhung limestone cave/roof climbing. Jugs everywhere. Beware of ground fall potential and have a good belayer. Most routes have glue-ins. Don't clip anything that looks rusty.
